   yields an upper limit of 21 M(Earth) for the companion mass, supporting
   the finding.
   Conclusions. CoRoT-7b is very likely the first Super-Earth with a
   measured radius. This object illustrates what will probably become a
   common situation with missions such as Kepler, namely the need to
   establish the planetary origin of transits in the absence of a firm
   radial velocity detection and mass measurement. The composition of
   CoRoT-7b remains loosely constrained without a precise mass. A very high
   surface temperature on its irradiated face, approximate to 1800-2600 K
