  abstract={We report on the discovery and validation of Kepler-452b, a transiting planet identified by a search through the 4 years of data collected by NASA’s Kepler Mission. This possibly rocky ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn3.gif] {${1.63}_{-0.20}^{+0.23}$} ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn4.gif] {${R}_{\oplus }$} planet orbits its G2 host star every ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn5.gif] {${384.843}_{-0.012}^{+0.007}$} days, the longest orbital period for a small ( ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn6.gif] {${R}_{\rm{P}}\lt 2$} ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn7.gif] {${R}_{\oplus }$} ) transiting exoplanet to date. The likelihood that this planet has a rocky composition lies between 49% and 62%. The star has an effective temperature of 5757 ± 85 K and a ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn8.gif] {$\mathrm{log}g$} of 4.32 ± 0.09. At a mean orbital separation of ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn9.gif] {${1.046}_{-0.015}^{+0.019}$} AU, this small planet is well within the optimistic habitable zone of its star (recent Venus/early Mars), experiencing only 10% more flux than Earth receives from the Sun today, and slightly outside the conservative habitable zone (runaway greenhouse/maximum greenhouse). The star is slightly larger and older than the Sun, with a present radius of ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn10.gif] {${1.11}_{-0.09}^{+0.15}$} ##IMG## [http://ej.iop.org/images/1538-3881/150/2/56/aj515345ieqn11.gif] {${R}_{\odot }$} and an estimated age of ∼6 Gyr. Thus, Kepler-452b has likely always been in the habitable zone and should remain there for another ∼3 Gyr.}
