   of up to 90 parts-per-million despite the presence of ammonia clouds. We
   also find that atmospheric refraction, as opposed to clouds or haze,
   determines the minimum altitude that could be probed during mid-transit.
   Self-consistent exoplanet atmosphere models show good agreement with
   Saturn's transmission spectrum but fail to reproduce a large absorption
   feature near 3.4 $\mu$m, likely caused by gaseous ethane and a C-H
   stretching mode of an unknown aliphatic hydrocarbon. This large feature
   is located in one of the Spitzer Space Telescope bandpasses and could
   alter interpretations of transmission spectra if not properly modeled.
   The large signal in Saturn's transmission spectrum suggests that
   transmission spectroscopy of cold, long-period gaseous exoplanets should
   be possible with current and future observatories. Motivated by these
   results, we briefly consider the feasibility of. using a survey to
   search for and characterize cold exoplanets that are analogous to
   Jupiter and Saturn utilizing a target-of-opportunity approach.},
